1
00:00:17,067 --> 00:00:20,300
HAMMOND:  Tonight,
James falls out of a boat.

2
00:00:20,333 --> 00:00:23,033
I have a fight
with a gear lever.

3
00:00:23,067 --> 00:00:24,333
-And...
-Hello.

4
00:00:24,367 --> 00:00:26,633
Oh, dear.
This is a bit embarrassing.

5
00:00:34,433 --> 00:00:37,533
Hello and welcome to
what's left of  Top Gear.

6
00:00:37,567 --> 00:00:39,200
And tonight's
programme is not,

7
00:00:39,233 --> 00:00:41,133
as I'm sure you've guessed,
a normal one.

8
00:00:41,167 --> 00:00:42,667
In fact, what we're
going to do is show you

9
00:00:42,700 --> 00:00:45,167
two films that were shot
for the last series.

10
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:46,867
Yes, the second one
is tremendous

11
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:48,067
and that'll be
coming up later.

12
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:50,100
But I want to start with this.

13
00:00:50,133 --> 00:00:51,633
It's a Jaguar E-Type.

14
00:00:51,667 --> 00:00:54,867
And thanks to
rocketing classic car prices,

15
00:00:54,900 --> 00:00:58,533
it's now worth
about 200 grand.

16
00:00:58,567 --> 00:01:00,533
And it's the same
story with these two.

17
00:01:00,567 --> 00:01:04,133
The Ferrari Daytona
and the Aston Martin DB5.

18
00:01:04,167 --> 00:01:06,800
Around 20 years ago,
you'd have been able
to buy either of these

19
00:01:06,833 --> 00:01:08,567
for around 80,000 pounds.

20
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:13,067
But today, the Ferrari,
700,000 pounds.

21
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:16,400
The Aston Martin,
probably a million.

22
00:01:16,433 --> 00:01:18,667
But there are still
some classic cars around

23
00:01:18,700 --> 00:01:20,800
that you can buy
for reasonable money.

24
00:01:20,833 --> 00:01:22,667
The question is, should you?

25
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:26,067
Well, to find out,
the producers told me,
Richard, and Jeremy

26
00:01:26,067 --> 00:01:28,400
to go and buy
a classic car apiece.

27
00:01:28,433 --> 00:01:29,733
And then turn up
with them

28
00:01:29,767 --> 00:01:32,467
at an old railway station
in Buckinghamshire.

29
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:34,567
They said we were
going to spend a few days

30
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:37,067
living the classic
car experience.

31
00:01:37,100 --> 00:01:40,067
English country lanes,
warm brown beer,

32
00:01:40,067 --> 00:01:42,533
and lots of fellow
enthusiasts to talk to.

33
00:01:42,567 --> 00:01:46,467
Basically, Jeremy's
idea of hell.

34
00:01:51,467 --> 00:01:53,700
HAMMOND:  This was
the meeting point.

35
00:01:55,500 --> 00:02:01,767
And I was the first to arrive
in my 1972 MGB GT.

36
00:02:02,933 --> 00:02:04,633
This is it.

37
00:02:05,367 --> 00:02:07,767
This is the daddy.

38
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:11,133
Think of a small,
classic, British sports car

39
00:02:11,167 --> 00:02:15,800
and you are thinking
of this, the MGB GT.

40
00:02:15,833 --> 00:02:17,667
Mechanically... (EXCLAIMS)

41
00:02:17,700 --> 00:02:19,633
...it's not a bad example
of what is undoubtedly

42
00:02:19,667 --> 00:02:23,333
Britain's most
popular classic car.

43
00:02:23,367 --> 00:02:25,800
At this point,
I was interrupted

44
00:02:25,833 --> 00:02:28,500
by the arrival of
Captain Cheerful.

45
00:02:29,833 --> 00:02:32,800
I say. That is pretty.

46
00:02:32,833 --> 00:02:34,200
Why are we doing this?

47
00:02:34,233 --> 00:02:35,567
What? What do you mean why?

48
00:02:35,600 --> 00:02:37,433
Look at it, 'cause of
everything about the day,

49
00:02:37,467 --> 00:02:42,467
the location, old trains,
classic cars, tinkering.

50
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:46,233
Hammond, listen, nobody
buys a classic television.

51
00:02:46,267 --> 00:02:47,367
They don't say,
"Look, you have to

52
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:49,100
"bang it on the top
to make the picture work

53
00:02:49,133 --> 00:02:50,667
"and it's black and white

54
00:02:50,700 --> 00:02:52,367
"and then you have
to stand up to change
the channel."

55
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:54,533
So why would you buy
a classic car?

56
00:02:54,567 --> 00:02:57,067
Because, well, look at it.

57
00:02:57,100 --> 00:03:00,600
CLARKSON: No, I admit,
Fiat 124 Spider.
Incredibly pretty.

58
00:03:00,633 --> 00:03:02,500
Designed by
the same man who did

59
00:03:02,533 --> 00:03:05,133
the Ferrari 275 GTS,
Lancia Fulvia,

60
00:03:05,167 --> 00:03:06,533
De Tomaso Pantera.

61
00:03:06,567 --> 00:03:09,500
But it will go wrong
all the time.

62
00:03:09,533 --> 00:03:12,933
Yes, that's the point.
Then you can stop
and fix it yourself.

63
00:03:12,967 --> 00:03:14,500
This is not just a car.

64
00:03:14,533 --> 00:03:17,267
It's something to
do at the weekends,
it's a project.

65
00:03:17,300 --> 00:03:19,667
The Hoover Dam was a project.

66
00:03:19,700 --> 00:03:23,633
A broken down car is
an inconvenience. It is.

67
00:03:23,667 --> 00:03:27,267
And yours will
break down even more
'cause it's an MGB GT.

68
00:03:27,300 --> 00:03:29,567
Deliciously and
delightfully simple. It's...

69
00:03:29,600 --> 00:03:31,333
-Whoa!
-What? What, what?

70
00:03:31,367 --> 00:03:33,333
Has there been a knife
fight in the back of it?

71
00:03:33,367 --> 00:03:35,567
Look at it.
The heritage, the history.

72
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:38,233
It's... This was
the poor man's E-Type.

73
00:03:38,700 --> 00:03:40,567
It's horrid.

74
00:03:40,600 --> 00:03:44,700
CLARKSON:  Soon we realised
there wasn't an elephant
in the room.

75
00:03:44,733 --> 00:03:47,300
What do you think
the elephant will be driving?

76
00:03:48,133 --> 00:03:49,867
Well, it'll be a Triumph.

77
00:03:49,900 --> 00:03:52,900
But I've thought about this,
it'll be, I think, a TR7.

78
00:03:52,933 --> 00:03:55,967
Because he won't expect us
to expect that.

79
00:03:56,067 --> 00:03:57,467
-He'll think that'll...
-Stag.

80
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,433
-But that's too obvious.
-No.

81
00:03:59,467 --> 00:04:01,900
It's a Peugeot.
And that's right and proper.

82
00:04:01,933 --> 00:04:04,333
'Cause he's old
and he never goes
faster than one.

83
00:04:04,367 --> 00:04:05,967
He is basically
a Peugeot himself.

84
00:04:06,067 --> 00:04:09,967
Is it very quiet? Or has it...

85
00:04:10,067 --> 00:04:11,167
(MAY GREETING IN FRENCH)

86
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:13,067
-HAMMOND: It's electric!
-(CLARKSON LAUGHS)

87
00:04:13,067 --> 00:04:14,267
Why isn't it running?

88
00:04:14,300 --> 00:04:16,600
(STAMMERS)
I'm just saving petrol.

89
00:04:16,633 --> 00:04:18,667
CLARKSON:
James, why isn't it running?

90
00:04:18,700 --> 00:04:19,700
What do you think?

91
00:04:19,733 --> 00:04:21,467
HAMMOND:
It's extremely pretty.

92
00:04:23,133 --> 00:04:24,900
-That is a pretty car.
-CLARKSON: Pretty.

93
00:04:25,267 --> 00:04:29,633
MAY: Peugeot 304
Decapotable S.

94
00:04:29,667 --> 00:04:32,200
HAMMOND: That
means convertible.
MAY: It does, yes.

95
00:04:32,233 --> 00:04:34,400
-CLARKSON: Decapitated.
-Beheaded, yes.

96
00:04:34,433 --> 00:04:36,133
-Is this you or him?
-It's mine.

97
00:04:36,167 --> 00:04:37,300
Hello, hello.

98
00:04:37,333 --> 00:04:40,200
Britain's most
popular classic.
Look at it.

99
00:04:40,233 --> 00:04:41,400
So that must be yours.

100
00:04:41,433 --> 00:04:43,600
-BOTH: Yes.
-I sort of approve of that.

101
00:04:43,633 --> 00:04:45,500
The only problem is
it's the American spec,

102
00:04:45,533 --> 00:04:47,467
it's lived all of
its life in California.

103
00:04:47,500 --> 00:04:49,333
-Those wheels are all wrong.
-I know.

104
00:04:49,367 --> 00:04:51,100
They had to raise it,

105
00:04:51,133 --> 00:04:53,400
because to get the headlights
the American height
above the road,

106
00:04:53,433 --> 00:04:55,400
they raised the whole car.

107
00:04:55,433 --> 00:04:56,733
And that ruined
the ride height,

108
00:04:56,767 --> 00:04:58,433
and the wheels are,
as you say, wrong.

109
00:04:58,467 --> 00:05:00,200
MAY: Anyway,
let's be positive about it.

110
00:05:00,233 --> 00:05:02,600
We've all got cars
styled by Pininfarina.

111
00:05:02,633 --> 00:05:03,667
He hasn't.

112
00:05:03,700 --> 00:05:05,100
-I have.
-No.

113
00:05:05,133 --> 00:05:06,867
This was styled
by Pininfarina?

114
00:05:06,900 --> 00:05:09,167
Pininfarina, yeah, because
the convertible version
came out first

115
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:11,733
and a couple years later,
Pininfarina turned it
into this.

116
00:05:11,767 --> 00:05:13,533
Pininfarina's dog.

117
00:05:14,567 --> 00:05:16,700
CLARKSON:  With the classic
British weather beckoning,

118
00:05:16,733 --> 00:05:20,333
we set off for a classic,
classic car drive.

119
00:05:20,367 --> 00:05:22,467
-Where, which way
are you going to... Oh...
-Through the gate.

120
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:25,100
-Through the puddle.
-'Cause this is the S,
remember.

121
00:05:25,133 --> 00:05:26,800
Go on!

122
00:05:27,467 --> 00:05:29,233
Oh, that sounds mighty.

123
00:05:29,267 --> 00:05:30,967
Here we go!

124
00:05:40,533 --> 00:05:42,833
This is everything
I hoped it would be.

125
00:05:42,867 --> 00:05:43,967
It's an experience.

126
00:05:44,067 --> 00:05:47,067
I can feel things
that are going on.

127
00:05:47,100 --> 00:05:48,800
I'm involved in it.

128
00:05:51,833 --> 00:05:53,333
There are those who say

129
00:05:53,367 --> 00:05:56,400
there is no better sound
in the motoring world

130
00:05:56,433 --> 00:05:59,800
than the 1.8 litre engine
exactly like that one.

131
00:06:02,433 --> 00:06:05,300
Oh, that does sound brilliant.
That's a proper car.

132
00:06:07,167 --> 00:06:11,267
HAMMOND:  In the Peugeot,
James was upbeat as well.

133
00:06:11,300 --> 00:06:12,967
This Peugeot,
I think you will agree,

134
00:06:13,067 --> 00:06:14,500
is charming.

135
00:06:14,533 --> 00:06:18,533
It is interesting.
It's French,
it's a bit leftfield.

136
00:06:18,567 --> 00:06:20,067
But I mean, everything works.

137
00:06:20,067 --> 00:06:22,467
Look, I mean,
the windscreen wipers
are working.

138
00:06:23,533 --> 00:06:25,267
Erm...

139
00:06:25,300 --> 00:06:27,067
Yeah, there's a clock.

140
00:06:28,633 --> 00:06:31,467
HAMMOND:
Meanwhile, in the Fiat...

141
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:35,533
This car is
absolutely horrible.

142
00:06:35,567 --> 00:06:36,967
I mean the driving position,

143
00:06:37,067 --> 00:06:39,767
they put the steering wheel
directly above the pedals,

144
00:06:39,800 --> 00:06:42,833
so to get comfortable,
your arms have to be

145
00:06:42,867 --> 00:06:45,900
the same length as your legs.
And mine aren't.

146
00:06:47,667 --> 00:06:50,433
Steaming up slightly.
I'll just engage the heater.

147
00:06:51,700 --> 00:06:52,767
Oh.

148
00:06:52,800 --> 00:06:54,600
Heater's not working.

149
00:06:54,633 --> 00:06:57,400
Welcome to 1970s
classic motoring.

150
00:06:58,200 --> 00:07:00,167
And a few moments later,

151
00:07:00,200 --> 00:07:02,900
James made it
even more authentic.

152
00:07:02,933 --> 00:07:04,867
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

153
00:07:04,900 --> 00:07:07,633
Hang on, hang on,
it's conking. Here it goes.

154
00:07:11,100 --> 00:07:12,800
Don't stop.

155
00:07:14,233 --> 00:07:17,100
Seven minutes and two miles
into the journey,

156
00:07:17,133 --> 00:07:18,833
he's broken down.

157
00:07:19,933 --> 00:07:21,833
With the help of
a kindly local...

158
00:07:21,867 --> 00:07:23,067
HAMMOND: Pushing.
CLARKSON: Pushing.

159
00:07:23,100 --> 00:07:24,367
MAY: Okay.
HAMMOND: Pushing.

160
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:25,933
CLARKSON:  ...we got
James going again.

161
00:07:25,967 --> 00:07:27,467
-Here we go.
-HAMMOND: Maybe you
could dump the clutch.

162
00:07:27,500 --> 00:07:29,167
CLARKSON: Dump
the clutch, James.
MAN: There you go.

163
00:07:29,200 --> 00:07:31,333
-(ENGINE TURNS ON)
-Yes, thank you!

164
00:07:31,367 --> 00:07:32,833
MAY: I can't stop.

165
00:07:32,867 --> 00:07:34,500
Now, I'm having to leave them.
That's a bit poor, isn't it,

166
00:07:34,533 --> 00:07:36,833
but I'm sure they'll catch up.

167
00:07:38,233 --> 00:07:41,300
We're off again.
That's all part of it.

168
00:07:43,333 --> 00:07:45,133
Nice man helped us.

169
00:07:45,167 --> 00:07:47,533
You see, we'd never
have met that nice man
if it wasn't for our cars.

170
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:55,133
CLARKSON: (ON RADIO)  Is this
really your top speed, James?

171
00:07:55,167 --> 00:07:57,467
Pretty much, yeah.

172
00:07:57,500 --> 00:08:01,067
CLARKSON:  For once though,
I was quite glad
he was holding me up.

173
00:08:02,433 --> 00:08:03,733
Right.

174
00:08:03,767 --> 00:08:06,733
No faster than this
or the wheels will fall off.

175
00:08:08,067 --> 00:08:09,833
These are aftermarket wheels.

176
00:08:09,867 --> 00:08:12,767
They have oval-shaped holes
where the nuts go through.

177
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:18,367
And if you go above say,
50, they just fall off.

178
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:22,067
Luckily, before there was
a chance for that to happen...

179
00:08:23,067 --> 00:08:24,833
Bloody hell, not again.

180
00:08:24,867 --> 00:08:26,600
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

181
00:08:27,500 --> 00:08:29,467
(ON RADIO)
I've gone again, sorry.

182
00:08:30,733 --> 00:08:34,067
Tell me what that is
coming out
the back of your car.

183
00:08:34,100 --> 00:08:35,600
MAY: That is...
HAMMOND: Oil.

184
00:08:35,633 --> 00:08:37,900
This is...
This is classic car motoring.

185
00:08:37,933 --> 00:08:40,833
Next Thursday,
I'll take a day off work,
take the old girl out,

186
00:08:40,867 --> 00:08:43,267
get the roof down,
Thursday comes, it's raining.

187
00:08:43,300 --> 00:08:44,700
-Yeah.
-Well, yeah.

188
00:08:44,733 --> 00:08:46,233
-And your car breaks down.
-The rain doesn't stop it.

189
00:08:46,267 --> 00:08:48,067
The rain makes it
more interesting.

190
00:08:48,067 --> 00:08:49,200
It doesn't.

191
00:08:49,233 --> 00:08:50,833
Just standing here
on a warm sunny day

192
00:08:50,867 --> 00:08:51,967
would be boring and ordinary.

193
00:08:52,067 --> 00:08:53,833
This is more of a challenge!

194
00:08:53,867 --> 00:08:57,767
CLARKSON:  Hammond
and I then did another
classic car workout.

195
00:08:57,800 --> 00:08:58,867
MAY: Push like hell.

196
00:08:58,900 --> 00:09:00,067
CLARKSON: Yes, just shut up.

197
00:09:00,100 --> 00:09:02,200
We are pushing hard.
We are pushing.

198
00:09:02,233 --> 00:09:03,533
(ENGINE STARTS)

199
00:09:03,567 --> 00:09:05,333
MAY: Here we go.

200
00:09:05,600 --> 00:09:07,600
Come on, chaps, let's go.

201
00:09:12,333 --> 00:09:15,500
What an absolutely
horrible day.

202
00:09:20,433 --> 00:09:21,767
The Peugeot is getting better.

203
00:09:21,800 --> 00:09:24,467
It's responding to
sympathetic treatment.

204
00:09:25,867 --> 00:09:27,900
That's the thing
you have to remember
about old machinery.

205
00:09:27,933 --> 00:09:30,067
You have to form
a bond with it.

206
00:09:30,100 --> 00:09:32,400
-(ENGINE SPUTTERING)
-Oh, bollocks.

207
00:09:34,100 --> 00:09:35,800
Don't stop.

208
00:09:39,933 --> 00:09:42,500
CLARKSON:  At this point,
even Hammond was tiring

209
00:09:42,533 --> 00:09:45,500
of the classic
car camaraderie.

210
00:09:45,533 --> 00:09:47,067
We've weighed it up
and we've decided

211
00:09:47,100 --> 00:09:49,067
we've helped him
enough today, frankly.

212
00:09:49,067 --> 00:09:50,433
(HORN HONKS)

213
00:09:50,467 --> 00:09:52,367
HAMMOND: (ON RADIO)
James, your car doesn't work.

214
00:09:53,367 --> 00:09:55,233
(HORN HONKS)

215
00:09:59,300 --> 00:10:03,067
CLARKSON: (ON RADIO)
Hammond, do you think you'll
be able to buy an alternator

216
00:10:03,100 --> 00:10:06,167
for a 1970s
Peugeot in Burford?

217
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:08,600
HAMMOND: (ON RADIO)  No, no.

218
00:10:08,633 --> 00:10:11,967
A very nice oven glove
with a cat on it, yes.

219
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:15,800
CLARKSON:  Or some jam in
a gingham pot of some sort.

220
00:10:15,833 --> 00:10:19,267
But alternators for
1970s Peugeots, no.

221
00:10:24,500 --> 00:10:27,333
CLARKSON:  Later that day,
we were all reunited.

222
00:10:27,367 --> 00:10:29,100
And the producers
said we should do

223
00:10:29,133 --> 00:10:33,967
what all classic
car enthusiasts do
after a short drive.

224
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,767
Go immediately into a garage
to do a bit of tinkering.

225
00:10:39,267 --> 00:10:41,000
(RUSTLING)

226
00:10:43,367 --> 00:10:45,433
(CLATTERING)

227
00:10:48,233 --> 00:10:50,967
There you go, my beauty.
There you go.

228
00:11:01,167 --> 00:11:02,867
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

229
00:11:10,067 --> 00:11:12,500
Hold tight. You win again!

230
00:11:14,067 --> 00:11:17,600
WOMAN: (ON RADIO)
Sit back, enjoy the fireworks.

231
00:11:17,633 --> 00:11:19,633
Let's bring in the New Year.

232
00:11:22,067 --> 00:11:23,767
(CLATTERING)

233
00:11:25,867 --> 00:11:27,833
WOMAN: (ON RADIO)
...Jane, producing today,
is looking forward

234
00:11:27,867 --> 00:11:29,800
to seeing her valentine,
Paul, this evening.

235
00:11:29,833 --> 00:11:33,433
Nicola wants to
send a happy Valentines
to her niece Ella.

236
00:11:33,467 --> 00:11:36,533
And I promised my valentine
a big kiss later today.

237
00:11:36,567 --> 00:11:38,533
And I'm going to go
home and give Chris...

238
00:11:38,567 --> 00:11:40,633
(CLATTERING)

239
00:11:41,767 --> 00:11:43,067
(BELL DINGS)

