00:11:43,067 --> 00:11:44,600
-(BIRDS TWEETING)
-(DOOR CREAKS)

241
00:11:44,633 --> 00:11:46,533
CLARKSON:  When a cuckoo told
us that spring had sprung,

242
00:11:46,567 --> 00:11:49,133
we emerged from our nests.

243
00:11:49,167 --> 00:11:51,633
And not only were
our cars transformed,

244
00:11:53,067 --> 00:11:54,533
so was I.

245
00:11:54,567 --> 00:11:56,867
-I say, here.
-Oh, yeah.

246
00:11:56,900 --> 00:11:58,767
Checkerboard, nice work.

247
00:11:58,800 --> 00:12:00,733
Oh!

248
00:12:00,767 --> 00:12:01,967
MAY: Harnesses.

249
00:12:02,067 --> 00:12:03,467
CLARKSON: Look at those seats.

250
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:05,100
HAMMOND: Seats, hello.
Bucket seats.
CLARKSON: Wow!

251
00:12:05,133 --> 00:12:06,333
HAMMOND: Racing seats.

252
00:12:06,367 --> 00:12:08,867
And stainless steel
exhaust front to back.

253
00:12:08,900 --> 00:12:11,467
-You're kidding.
-Yep, all the way.

254
00:12:11,500 --> 00:12:14,400
But gentlemen,
behold the achievement.

255
00:12:14,433 --> 00:12:16,067
HAMMOND: Losing the bumpers...
CLARKSON: Bumpers gone.

256
00:12:16,100 --> 00:12:17,333
HAMMOND: Genius.

257
00:12:17,367 --> 00:12:19,400
CLARKSON: Coils, sliced
away top and bottom.

258
00:12:19,433 --> 00:12:21,067
So it's now lower.

259
00:12:21,067 --> 00:12:23,667
New Abarth wheels.

260
00:12:23,700 --> 00:12:25,067
Black bonnet.

261
00:12:25,067 --> 00:12:28,233
And, of course, at the front,
a brace of Cibies.

262
00:12:28,267 --> 00:12:30,067
So essentially this is
how it should've looked.

263
00:12:30,100 --> 00:12:32,533
-It's how it was
when it was sold in Italy.
-Yes.

264
00:12:32,567 --> 00:12:34,500
The Americans
totally ruined it

265
00:12:34,533 --> 00:12:36,433
by lifting it up and putting
stupid bumpers on it.

266
00:12:36,467 --> 00:12:38,933
I've taken it back
to original spec.

267
00:12:38,967 --> 00:12:40,267
I have been busy.

268
00:12:40,300 --> 00:12:41,600
It's nice.

269
00:12:41,633 --> 00:12:43,267
So, James, what car
have you been working on?

270
00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:44,633
(LAUGHS) Funny.

271
00:12:44,667 --> 00:12:47,067
CLARKSON: No, wait,
I can see how busy he's been.

272
00:12:47,067 --> 00:12:50,233
You've painted
your headlights yellow
and it's taken you...

273
00:12:50,267 --> 00:12:51,467
October, November, December,
January, February...

274
00:12:51,500 --> 00:12:54,067
Yeah, but I've also
rebuilt and improved

275
00:12:54,100 --> 00:12:55,700
and completely
mended the engine.

276
00:12:55,733 --> 00:12:57,133
-CLARKSON: You mean you've
just made your car work.
-Yeah.

277
00:12:57,167 --> 00:12:58,733
Except you won't be able
to see where you're going

278
00:12:58,767 --> 00:13:00,733
'cause you've gone for
the old French
headlight system.

279
00:13:00,767 --> 00:13:02,067
-Yes.
-James.

280
00:13:02,067 --> 00:13:03,633
It's authentically dangerous.
Yes.

281
00:13:03,667 --> 00:13:05,867
HAMMOND: What is that
on your steering wheel?

282
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:08,567
That's just... In case I had
to move the steering wheel

283
00:13:08,600 --> 00:13:11,067
while I had oily hands
from working on the engine.

284
00:13:11,067 --> 00:13:14,900
CLARKSON: Somebody
manufactures a condom
for the steering wheel?

285
00:13:14,933 --> 00:13:16,300
It turns out they do, yeah.

286
00:13:16,333 --> 00:13:18,767
And if you're a monk
with hair round the sides

287
00:13:18,800 --> 00:13:21,667
but not on the top,
it's also a shower cap.

288
00:13:21,700 --> 00:13:23,433
(BOTH LAUGHING)

289
00:13:33,333 --> 00:13:36,833
CLARKSON:  Having spent
six months in hibernation
doing tinkering,

290
00:13:36,867 --> 00:13:40,800
even I couldn't wait to take
my car out for a drive.

291
00:13:44,433 --> 00:13:46,100
Tell me this car
doesn't look brilliant.

292
00:13:46,133 --> 00:13:47,933
Tell me, I dare you.

293
00:13:47,967 --> 00:13:51,133
Actually, it does look
a lot better than it did,
I'll give you that.

294
00:13:51,167 --> 00:13:54,733
CLARKSON: (ON RADIO)
You have polished that
turd well, Hammond.

295
00:13:57,400 --> 00:14:01,267
Oh, I'm loving...
This is tremendous.

296
00:14:02,700 --> 00:14:05,100
Driving a car like this
with big bumpers

297
00:14:05,133 --> 00:14:07,333
and idiotic ride height
in the rain,

298
00:14:07,367 --> 00:14:09,433
utter misery. But now...

299
00:14:10,967 --> 00:14:12,700
(CHUCKLES)

300
00:14:12,733 --> 00:14:17,667
An English spring day in a car
with a matte black bonnet.
I'm happy.

301
00:14:17,700 --> 00:14:20,067
So we plunged
into the Cotswolds

302
00:14:20,100 --> 00:14:24,267
looking for
classic car adventures.

303
00:14:24,300 --> 00:14:27,333
Now, normally at this point,
we would do the news!

304
00:14:27,367 --> 00:14:28,833
Or maybe we would
watch a famous person

305
00:14:28,867 --> 00:14:31,667
blatting around our test track
in a Vauxhall Astra,

306
00:14:31,700 --> 00:14:33,400
but obviously, we can't do
either of those things,

307
00:14:33,433 --> 00:14:36,900
so instead we're going to
give you some information.

308
00:14:36,933 --> 00:14:38,733
Yes, the producers told us,

309
00:14:38,767 --> 00:14:40,800
after we'd modified
our classic cars,

310
00:14:40,833 --> 00:14:44,433
that during our journey
we would be facing
various challenges,

311
00:14:44,467 --> 00:14:47,700
and that points
would be awarded
to whoever did best.

312
00:14:47,733 --> 00:14:50,100
However, they also
told us that we would

313
00:14:50,133 --> 00:14:52,600
lose points for
every breakdown we had.

314
00:14:52,633 --> 00:14:54,700
So you've basically
lost already, then?

315
00:14:54,733 --> 00:14:56,800
No, rubbish.
Not necessarily, actually.

316
00:14:56,833 --> 00:14:59,433
And that the person who
ended up with the most points

317
00:14:59,467 --> 00:15:02,567
would get a special prize.

318
00:15:11,500 --> 00:15:17,400
CLARKSON:  Eager to show off
our newly-fettled cars,
I came up with an idea.

319
00:15:17,433 --> 00:15:19,867
The great thing about England
at this time of year is that

320
00:15:19,900 --> 00:15:23,367
every single village,
pretty much
every single weekend,

321
00:15:23,400 --> 00:15:26,233
hosts some kind of
classic car event.

322
00:15:26,267 --> 00:15:27,667
People gather in a field,

323
00:15:27,700 --> 00:15:30,700
talk about their adenoids
and the "old girl" and...

324
00:15:31,867 --> 00:15:34,767
Well, I think we should
find one and go to it.

325
00:15:37,567 --> 00:15:42,667
So we headed immediately for
a leafy village in Wiltshire.

326
00:15:44,167 --> 00:15:47,667
Can you imagine
what a classic car show

327
00:15:47,700 --> 00:15:51,433
will be like
in a village such as this?

328
00:15:51,467 --> 00:15:56,133
Old men in flat caps,
little children
scampering around.

329
00:15:56,167 --> 00:16:00,400
Stalls selling tea towels
with Morris Minors on them.

330
00:16:00,433 --> 00:16:02,367
MAY: Making your own chutney.

331
00:16:02,400 --> 00:16:04,900
Putting people in the stocks.
All that sort of stuff.

332
00:16:05,600 --> 00:16:07,300
However...

333
00:16:17,267 --> 00:16:21,167
ANNOUNCER:  Welcome, everyone.
Welcome to Castle Combe
for Japfest.

334
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:22,900
Japfest?

335
00:16:25,067 --> 00:16:27,067
MAY: Mitsubishi,
Mitsubishi, Mitsubishi,

336
00:16:27,067 --> 00:16:31,400
Mitsubishi, Mitsubishi,
that's a Mitsubishi.

337
00:16:31,433 --> 00:16:35,367
So it's probably fair to say
we've got this slightly wrong.

338
00:16:35,400 --> 00:16:39,333
Nevertheless, we were among
fellow car enthusiasts.

339
00:16:39,367 --> 00:16:42,467
And once we'd got Hammond
properly dressed,

340
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:45,733
we were treated to
a spot of light drifting.

341
00:16:53,433 --> 00:16:54,967
(TYRES SCREECHING)

342
00:16:55,067 --> 00:16:57,067
That's June Whitfield
in that one.

343
00:16:57,067 --> 00:16:58,767
-Is it?
-Yeah.

344
00:17:02,067 --> 00:17:03,533
David Attenborough,
here he is.

345
00:17:03,567 --> 00:17:05,300
HAMMOND:
He loves a bit of this.

346
00:17:06,800 --> 00:17:08,133
That's a good one.

347
00:17:08,167 --> 00:17:10,133
This'll be good.
Darcey Bussell,
she is brilliant.

348
00:17:10,167 --> 00:17:11,867
CLARKSON: Go on, Darcey.

349
00:17:13,667 --> 00:17:15,067
HAMMOND: That's a belter,
that was a good one.

350
00:17:15,067 --> 00:17:16,733
MAY: That's a good one, yes.

351
00:17:20,633 --> 00:17:22,300
What?

352
00:17:23,400 --> 00:17:25,800
It's not really that
sort of thing, is it?

353
00:17:26,867 --> 00:17:28,700
Right. "Even though your cars

354
00:17:28,733 --> 00:17:30,767
"aren't technically
Japanese..."

355
00:17:30,800 --> 00:17:33,133
-Well, not at all.
-Mine's completely French.

356
00:17:33,167 --> 00:17:37,400
"...the organisers
here will allow you
to do 10 laps of the track.

357
00:17:37,433 --> 00:17:42,067
"Points will be awarded
for the fastest time."

358
00:17:42,067 --> 00:17:44,200
We're not going out
at the same time
as these guys, are we?

359
00:17:44,233 --> 00:17:45,467
Not right now.

360
00:17:45,500 --> 00:17:47,900
Are we going to have
the track to ourselves?

361
00:17:47,933 --> 00:17:49,067
No... No?

362
00:17:49,067 --> 00:17:50,667
That's not right.

363
00:17:50,700 --> 00:17:55,267
No, we'll be out
with other enthusiasts
of the Japanese car.

364
00:17:55,300 --> 00:17:57,067
That's an...
Why would you do that

365
00:17:57,067 --> 00:17:59,067
in a 304 front
wheel drive convertible?

366
00:17:59,100 --> 00:18:02,567
Come on,
enter into the spirit of it.

367
00:18:02,600 --> 00:18:05,767
CLARKSON:  To make sure
he wasn't too much
of a nuisance on the circuit,

368
00:18:05,800 --> 00:18:11,067
Captain Sense of Direction
had taken some precautions.

369
00:18:11,100 --> 00:18:13,867
So down there,
that one's tight
with a bit of a crest.

370
00:18:13,900 --> 00:18:16,333
Got to watch out for that.
That's reasonably quick.

371
00:18:16,367 --> 00:18:18,467
Got to go slow for that.

372
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:22,267
CLARKSON:  And with that
taken care of, we began.

373
00:18:24,600 --> 00:18:28,067
Now the chassis in this car,
the Fiat 124 Spider,

374
00:18:28,067 --> 00:18:32,100
went on to be used
later in the Lada Riva.

375
00:18:32,133 --> 00:18:33,800
Oh, yeah.

376
00:18:34,933 --> 00:18:37,867
The engine though is
an absolute cracker.

377
00:18:37,900 --> 00:18:41,433
1750 CC, 16 valve, twin cam.

378
00:18:44,667 --> 00:18:48,733
This is what
my little MG was born to do.

379
00:18:50,300 --> 00:18:51,833
It's a sports car.

380
00:18:51,867 --> 00:18:56,100
Live rear axle,
1.8 litre B-series engine,

381
00:18:56,133 --> 00:18:58,700
pumping out
95 brake horsepower.

382
00:18:58,733 --> 00:19:00,500
That's just enough.

383
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:06,967
Now, the standard Peugeot 304
had 65 horsepower,

384
00:19:07,067 --> 00:19:08,733
but don't worry, viewers,

385
00:19:08,767 --> 00:19:13,767
because this is
the twin choke carburetted
S-version and has 74!

386
00:19:15,667 --> 00:19:18,800
Sadly, however,
today, that wasn't enough.

387
00:19:32,433 --> 00:19:34,267
Yeah, they're all past safely.

388
00:19:36,667 --> 00:19:39,767
Unfortunately, the man
who then overtook Hammond

389
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:41,967
didn't manage
his move quite so well.

390
00:19:45,967 --> 00:19:47,700
HAMMOND: And he's lost it.

391
00:19:47,733 --> 00:19:49,500
(LAUGHS)

392
00:19:49,733 --> 00:19:51,433
But then...

393
00:19:52,433 --> 00:19:54,300
A misfire is happening.

394
00:19:55,167 --> 00:19:58,267
Oh, no, I think I am unwell.

395
00:19:58,300 --> 00:20:01,867
Still, at least
I wasn't suffering alone.

396
00:20:03,233 --> 00:20:04,400
Yeah.

397
00:20:04,433 --> 00:20:07,633
Yeah, you see,
ah, the oil's been...

398
00:20:07,667 --> 00:20:10,767
It's sloshing
from side to side
as I corner hard.

399
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:13,367
And some of it
has sloshed out now.

400
00:20:13,400 --> 00:20:15,000
And that is sounding a bit,

401
00:20:15,033 --> 00:20:19,267
what classic car enthusiasts
call, "Bottom-endy."

402
00:20:19,300 --> 00:20:21,267
CLARKSON:  Having ruined
their cars too,

403
00:20:21,300 --> 00:20:24,200
James and Richard
came into the pits,

404
00:20:24,233 --> 00:20:27,733
where the producers
revealed our lap times.

405
00:20:27,767 --> 00:20:31,467
I happen to know that
when the Mazda MX5 owners club

406
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:32,867
meet here for a track day,

407
00:20:32,900 --> 00:20:36,100
so just ordinary people
who are vets and teachers,

408
00:20:36,133 --> 00:20:38,500
they lap in 1:25.

409
00:20:39,200 --> 00:20:41,067
-James May.
-Yes.

410
00:20:41,100 --> 00:20:43,133
(ALL LAUGHING)

411
00:20:43,167 --> 00:20:45,000
You're not starting
with a one, are you?

412
00:20:45,633 --> 00:20:47,467
Well, hang on.

413
00:20:47,500 --> 00:20:49,233
Not even close to a one.

414
00:20:49,267 --> 00:20:53,267
It's 2:17.19.

415
00:20:53,300 --> 00:20:54,333
That's big.

416
00:20:54,367 --> 00:20:57,933
Me, 1:52.17.

417
00:20:57,967 --> 00:20:59,067
That's under two.

418
00:20:59,100 --> 00:21:02,967
Richard Hammond, 1:51.65.

419
00:21:03,067 --> 00:21:04,233
Was that all that was in it?

420
00:21:04,267 --> 00:21:06,800
-That's half a second.
-(EXHALES SHARPLY)

421
00:21:06,833 --> 00:21:09,467
CLARKSON:  Keen to find out
why we were so slow,

422
00:21:09,500 --> 00:21:13,733
the producers told us to put
our cars on a rolling road,

423
00:21:13,767 --> 00:21:17,533
to see how much horsepower
they'd lost over the years.

424
00:21:17,567 --> 00:21:18,900
HAMMOND:
James, when it was new...

425
00:21:18,933 --> 00:21:20,400
CLARKSON: What did it use to
have when it was new?

426
00:21:20,433 --> 00:21:22,067
Seventy-four horsepower.

427
00:21:22,067 --> 00:21:23,833
-Seventy-four.
-HAMMOND: Whoa!

428
00:21:24,300 --> 00:21:25,600
CLARKSON: Oh, yeah, it's off.

429
00:21:25,633 --> 00:21:27,100
MAY: Here we go. Here we go.

430
00:21:27,133 --> 00:21:28,933
Oh, look, look! Oh!

431
00:21:30,233 --> 00:21:32,233
(LAUGHS)

432
00:21:34,300 --> 00:21:38,600
Fifty point two.
You've lost 24 horsepower.

433
00:21:38,633 --> 00:21:41,267
That's 33%
of your total power is gone.

434
00:21:41,300 --> 00:21:43,267
That's quite a lot, isn't it?

435
00:21:43,300 --> 00:21:46,600
HAMMOND:  Next, it was
the turn of the MGB.

436
00:21:46,633 --> 00:21:48,600
This is the most powerful
when it was new.

437
00:21:48,633 --> 00:21:50,333
Ninety-five,
we're looking for.

438
00:21:52,500 --> 00:21:53,767
-Whoa!
-Come on.

439
00:21:53,800 --> 00:21:56,300
HAMMOND:
It didn't go as I'd hoped.

440
00:22:00,100 --> 00:22:02,067
(BOTH LAUGHING HYSTERICALLY)

441
00:22:03,333 --> 00:22:05,367
MAY: Fifty-eight point eight.

442
00:22:05,400 --> 00:22:07,067
Your machine's wrong.

443
00:22:07,933 --> 00:22:10,500
Then it was the Fiat's turn.

444
00:22:11,733 --> 00:22:14,900
So, 85 is what it did have
when it was new.

445
00:22:14,933 --> 00:22:16,233
Fifty-five, I'm going for 55.

446
00:22:16,267 --> 00:22:18,300
Fifty-six,
I'm going to go for.

447
00:22:18,333 --> 00:22:20,633
-MAY: There it is.
-Here we go!

448
00:22:20,667 --> 00:22:22,367
Higher, higher!

449
00:22:22,833 --> 00:22:24,533
Oh, no!

450
00:22:25,533 --> 00:22:27,233
Oh!

451
00:22:28,467 --> 00:22:30,833
-Read it and weep!
-Sixty-eight point six.

452
00:22:30,867 --> 00:22:32,667
Yeah, but it's still
not a big number.

453
00:22:32,700 --> 00:22:34,067
Sixty-eight horsepower.

454
00:22:34,100 --> 00:22:36,200
You're applauding
lawnmower power.

455
00:22:36,233 --> 00:22:38,600
(CROWD CHEERS)

456
00:22:38,633 --> 00:22:41,600
CLARKSON:  Sadly, however,
the victory was hollow.

457
00:22:42,700 --> 00:22:44,400
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

458
00:22:47,933 --> 00:22:49,733
That is not a good sound.

459
00:22:51,600 --> 00:22:54,300
A classic car is
like a pet dog.

460
00:22:54,333 --> 00:22:56,900
One day it's going to
let you down and die.

461
00:22:58,500 --> 00:23:01,500
We therefore decided to do
something less taxing,

462
00:23:01,533 --> 00:23:03,300
like going to the pub.

463
00:23:03,333 --> 00:23:05,833
But that was trickier
than it sounded.

464
00:23:07,367 --> 00:23:09,833
Here's a pub. What about this?
We can go in here.

465
00:23:09,867 --> 00:23:12,433
No, it has
an illuminated sign for lager.

466
00:23:12,467 --> 00:23:14,733
Well, of course
it sells lager, it's a pub.

467
00:23:16,333 --> 00:23:18,367
Pub coming up on the right.

468
00:23:18,400 --> 00:23:20,800
Is this any good?

469
00:23:20,833 --> 00:23:23,267
They're having
a cheese and wine evening.

470
00:23:23,300 --> 00:23:24,633
Keep going.

471
00:23:24,667 --> 00:23:28,300
James has very specific
requirements about pubs.

472
00:23:28,333 --> 00:23:31,833
He won't go in a pub
if it has Sky Sports

473
00:23:31,867 --> 00:23:33,700
or if there's
a purple dinosaur

474
00:23:33,733 --> 00:23:36,200
in the back garden
with steps up its back.

475
00:23:36,233 --> 00:23:38,667
Or if there's a sign
saying children welcome.

476
00:23:38,700 --> 00:23:41,967
He doesn't like beams,
he doesn't like horse brasses.

477
00:23:42,067 --> 00:23:43,700
This may take a while.

478
00:23:48,333 --> 00:23:49,667
James, there's a pub up here.

479
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:51,400
What's the matter
with this one?

480
00:23:51,433 --> 00:23:54,933
Stickers in the window, flags,
and it calls itself a tavern.
Go.

481
